%md
## 1. Extract Vectors for Regression

Spark ML requires a special type "Vector" for representing features. Therefore we need to build these Vectors from all columns that we want to use as a vector.

result.msg:
1. Extract Vectors for Regression

Spark ML requires a special type “Vector” for representing features. Therefore we need to build these Vectors from all columns that we want to use as a vector.

paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.ml.linalg.Vectors

def extract_vector(row:Row, cols:Array[Int]) =
    Vectors.dense(cols.map(i => row.getDouble(i)).toArray)

println(extract_vector(Row("Bob",23.0), Array(1)))

// Use the following columns for extracting the Features
val columnNames = Array(
    "ts",
    "season",
    "year",
    "month",
    "hour",
    "holiday",
    "weekday",
    "workingday",
    "weather",
    "temperature",
    "apparent_temperature",
    "humidity",
    "wind_speed"
)
val cols = columnNames.map(n => ddata.schema.map(_.name).indexOf(n))

// Transform all records ddata into tuples (feature, counter)
// counter can be found in column row(16)
// the resulting columns should be called "features" and "counter"
val features_labels = ddata.map(row => (extract_vector(row, cols), row.getDouble(16)))
    .withColumnRenamed("_1","features")
    .withColumnRenamed("_2","counter")

// Peek inside the new dataframe
z.show(features_labels.limit(6))

# VectorAssembler instead of Manual Feature Extraction

Manual feature extraction (i.e. creation of the Vector) is a little bit tedious and not very comfortable. But luckily, there is a valuable helper called VectorAssembler.

We use it to automatically extract the columns

    season, year, month, hour, holiday, weekday, workingday, weather, 
    temperature, apparent_temperature, humidity, wind_speed

into the new output column 'features'

So we will again create a regression, but in a cleaner way.

1. Split Data into Training and Validation Set
2. Create Features Using Vector Assembler and Train Model
3. Predict Data
4. Evaluate Model
